{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b35362dc-fa34-4587-810e-46b97da3961d","content":"`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` tells MAUI not to inset your content for safe areas, but on **Android** you also need to opt into edge-to-edge rendering at the window level. Otherwise the system still reserves space for the status/nav bars.\n\n**In your `MainActivity.cs` (or a lifecycle handler):**\n\n```csharp\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\n// In OnCreate, after base call:\nWindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\nWindow.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\nWindow.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n```\n\n**On iOS**, also add the platform-specific attribute:\n\n```xml\nxmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n\n<ContentPage ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\" ...>\n```\n\n**And make sure your Image fills the space:**\n\n```xml\n<Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n       Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n       HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\"\n       VerticalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n```\n\nThe missing piece is almost always the Android `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(false)` call — without it, the OS insets your app's content regardless of what MAUI's layout engine does.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b0d102c6-0bac-477e-8f62-64a989214c00","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is working on a .NET MAUI app targeting .NET 10 and wants an image to go edge-to-edge (behind status bar and navigation bar). They've set `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common issue in .NET MAUI. Setting `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` isn't enough by itself. Let me think about what's needed:\n\n1. In .NET MAUI, to go truly edge-to-edge, you need to handle platform-specific configurations.\n\n2. On **Android**, you need to enable edge-to-edge display. \n\nIn .NET 10, the approach involves using the newer edge-to-edge APIs to make the window draw behind system bars rather than around them. On **iOS**, the safe area behavior is controlled through properties like `Page.IgnoreSafeArea` or platform-specific settings, though there might be additional nuances depending on the view hierarchy.\n\nFor .NET MAUI specifically, the key is setting `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` on iOS and ensuring the Image control uses `AspectFill` or `Fill` for the `Aspect` property to properly fill the available space. The `IgnoreSafeArea` property on individual views can also help, though support varies across different controls.\n\nOn Android, achieving edge-to-edge rendering requires configuring the status bar and navigation bar to be transparent...\n\nActually, I realize the core issue: Android requires explicit opt-in through `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(false)` in the MainActivity to allow content to extend behind system bars, whereas iOS just needs the safe area disabled in XAML. For .NET 10 on Android 15+, edge-to-edge is enforced by default, but older Android versions still need manual configuration. I should focus my answer on these platform-specific differences since that's likely what's preventing the image from going full-bleed.","outputTokens":1422,"requestId":"080A:187D22:A94840:C4665F:69F2AAC2"},"id":"3a16e1ca-d199-491d-aa9e-a57e27b15b18","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:05:35.540Z","parentId":"563a51cb-8a24-4076-8dce-081492fa7f41"}
